0
00:00:18,985 --> 00:00:20,976
"The big old owl flapped his wings
and yawned.

1
00:00:21,154 --> 00:00:23,748
It's much too late
and too many creatures about.

2
00:00:23,923 --> 00:00:27,086
She will surely get a scary fright.

3
00:00:27,260 --> 00:00:30,229
Where the alligators romp
and the frogs grow fat and orange...

4
00:00:30,397 --> 00:00:32,331
...the field mouse sings
to the owl kings...

5
00:00:32,499 --> 00:00:35,491
...with a voice
like a squeaky door hinge...

6
00:00:35,668 --> 00:00:37,966
...there lived a girl
who's sunny sweet...

7
00:00:38,138 --> 00:00:42,404
...and the children
call her Sticky Feet.

8
00:00:43,243 --> 00:00:46,940
With almond eyes
and golden curls...

9
00:00:47,113 --> 00:00:52,141
...she knew that swamps
are not for girls."

10
00:05:36,569 --> 00:05:40,266
Claire, the dreams
are getting stronger.

11
00:05:41,641 --> 00:05:44,235
All I'm saying, Claire,
is you gotta stop avoiding it.

12
00:05:47,413 --> 00:05:50,678
It's time we started to really deal
with this. It's important.

13
00:05:52,552 --> 00:05:54,247
Are you taking your medication?

14
00:05:55,655 --> 00:05:57,452
Doesn't help.

15
00:06:00,126 --> 00:06:02,060
It's evolving.

16
00:06:03,162 --> 00:06:08,156
I'd like to try hypnosis, a change.
We're ready.

17
00:06:13,773 --> 00:06:15,172
Is this a man-made problem...

18
00:06:15,341 --> 00:06:18,208
...or possibly the result
of global warming?

19
00:06:18,378 --> 00:06:21,347
Check into any inn or
bed-and-breakfast in Westmoreland...

20
00:06:21,514 --> 00:06:25,075
...and you'll notice a serious decline
in hunters and birdwatchers alike.

21
00:06:25,251 --> 00:06:27,310
But is it from their own doing?

22
00:06:27,487 --> 00:06:29,614
The blue-winged warbler
hasn't been seen here...

23
00:06:29,789 --> 00:06:31,723
...since last summer
in Westmoreland County.

24
00:06:31,891 --> 00:06:33,916
Perhaps this once-flourishing...

25
00:08:54,934 --> 00:08:56,231
- Claire?
- Mrs. O'Shea.

26
00:08:56,402 --> 00:08:59,428
Mercy, and this is Heidi.

27
00:09:00,339 --> 00:09:02,967
Welcome to Rose Marsh Farm.

28
00:09:13,219 --> 00:09:16,814
We don't get too many guests
this time of year, so...

29
00:09:20,426 --> 00:09:23,418
Here's your living room.

30
00:09:23,596 --> 00:09:27,032
There's wood and kindling
over there.

31
00:09:27,199 --> 00:09:28,427
Should keep you warm.

32
00:09:28,601 --> 00:09:31,661
The fireplace is working.
It's pretty straightforward.

33
00:09:31,837 --> 00:09:35,898
We get photographers
and birdwatchers in the summer.

34
00:09:36,876 --> 00:09:40,334
So if you'll follow me,
I'll show you the upstairs.

35
00:09:42,315 --> 00:09:46,149
- You're a writer?
- Yes.

36
00:09:47,053 --> 00:09:51,217
Well, you'll have lots of peace
and quiet, and plenty of space.

37
00:09:51,390 --> 00:09:53,358
I can guarantee you that.

38
00:09:57,496 --> 00:09:59,123
This is the master bedroom.

39
00:09:59,298 --> 00:10:01,994
There's extra linen in the closet.

40
00:10:03,669 --> 00:10:06,604
And here's the studio.

41
00:10:42,041 --> 00:10:45,704
The Manvilles and the Roses
settled the whole area.

42
00:10:50,783 --> 00:10:53,411
We call him Old Mister.

43
00:10:56,489 --> 00:10:57,888
And that's the marsh.

44
00:10:58,057 --> 00:11:00,525
Yeah, I'd steer clear of that,
if I was you.

45
00:11:00,693 --> 00:11:02,388
You can get lost in there
pretty quick.

46
00:11:02,561 --> 00:11:06,088
If you need anything, I'm the first
house on the way into town.

47
00:12:55,374 --> 00:12:58,935
"The big old owl flapped his wings
and yawned.

48
00:12:59,111 --> 00:13:01,636
What is a girl doing
in a swamp at night?

49
00:13:01,814 --> 00:13:04,783
It's much too late
and too many creatures about.

50
00:13:04,950 --> 00:13:08,545
She will surely get a scary fright."

51
00:13:09,355 --> 00:13:11,255
How do you make up your stories?

52
00:13:11,423 --> 00:13:15,325
I start by asking the question,
"What if?"

53
00:14:43,749 --> 00:14:45,341
- Oh, sorry.
- I'm sorry.

54
00:14:45,517 --> 00:14:47,644
- I didn't see you.
- It's all right. I'm so sorry.

55
00:14:47,820 --> 00:14:49,048
- Are you all right?
- Yes.

56
00:14:49,221 --> 00:14:51,155
All right, well, good morning,

57
00:14:51,323 --> 00:14:53,086
Good morning.

58
00:14:58,764 --> 00:14:59,992
Noah, Noah Pitney.

59
00:15:00,165 --> 00:15:03,100
That's the great thing
about being from a small town...

60
00:15:03,269 --> 00:15:07,103
...is you can introduce yourself
to anyone you bump into.

61
00:15:07,273 --> 00:15:09,605
- Right, Ernie?
- That's right.

62
00:15:10,643 --> 00:15:13,840
- Claire Holloway.
- Pleasure to meet you, Ms. Holloway.

63
00:15:14,013 --> 00:15:16,208
Nineteen fifty, miss.

64
00:15:17,783 --> 00:15:20,980
No, no, no, allow me, please.
This is country manners in action.

65
00:15:21,153 --> 00:15:23,621
Ernie, I just want to remind you
there's a game tonight.

66
00:15:23,789 --> 00:15:25,222
- Got it.
- I'll see you then.

67
00:15:26,625 --> 00:15:29,651
Oh, and please, put this on my tab.

68
00:15:32,531 --> 00:15:34,522
- This is for you.
- You don't have to do that.

69
00:15:34,700 --> 00:15:36,725
No, please, take it.
I've already read it.

70
00:15:36,902 --> 00:15:38,836
Help you get accustomed
to the town.

71
00:15:39,004 --> 00:15:40,869
Editor's got some
pretty eccentric views...

72
00:15:41,040 --> 00:15:43,372
...but, say, I bet he'd love
an interview with you.

73
00:15:43,776 --> 00:15:47,371
- You really that short on tourists?
- Come on, Claire, I have three nieces.

74
00:15:47,546 --> 00:15:49,673
"Star children's author
hits Westmoreland."

75
00:15:49,848 --> 00:15:51,975
That's pretty big stuff around here.

76
00:15:52,151 --> 00:15:53,584
I'm flattered.

77
00:15:54,920 --> 00:15:56,353
But?

78
00:15:59,224 --> 00:16:01,692
But I think I'm going to pass.

79
00:16:01,860 --> 00:16:05,159
That's all right. I'll just have
to interview yet another bingo winner.

80
00:16:05,631 --> 00:16:07,258
- You're the editor.
- I am, yeah.

81
00:16:07,433 --> 00:16:08,900
Also the local historian.

82
00:16:09,068 --> 00:16:11,002
Actually, I brought out
a book last year.

83
00:16:11,170 --> 00:16:13,730
I only, you know,
only printed 250 copies, but...

84
00:16:14,840 --> 00:16:18,674
- That's what my first one was.
- Really? So there's hope for me.

85
00:16:19,511 --> 00:16:21,376
Okay.

86
00:16:22,047 --> 00:16:23,571
Listen, if you need anything...

87
00:16:23,749 --> 00:16:27,378
...my number's on the back of
the paper, if you wanna call me.

88
00:16:30,322 --> 00:16:31,789
Bye.

89
00:17:08,327 --> 00:17:10,557
What if?

90
00:17:14,600 --> 00:17:17,831
What if, what if, what if, what?

91
00:21:09,901 --> 00:21:11,732
I could get used to
this country living.

92
00:21:11,903 --> 00:21:15,395
Yeah, well, I can...
I can appreciate that.

93
00:21:15,974 --> 00:21:18,807
I remember there was a time
when I covered crime...

94
00:21:18,977 --> 00:21:23,004
...for all the big dailies
all over the country.

95
00:21:25,450 --> 00:21:27,247
How did you end up here?

96
00:21:27,686 --> 00:21:32,089
It's weird. I always told myself
that I was never gonna come back.

97
00:21:32,257 --> 00:21:34,452
And then the editor's job came up...

98
00:21:34,626 --> 00:21:39,757
...and Philip Manville asked me
to do it and I said yes...

99
00:21:40,732 --> 00:21:43,599
...and I guess it just felt right
to come back.

100
00:21:43,769 --> 00:21:45,828
You know, I have my farm
and got a horse.

101
00:21:46,004 --> 00:21:48,632
And it's good. It's a good life.

102
00:21:49,608 --> 00:21:52,543
There. It's not perfect, but it'll work.

103
00:21:54,546 --> 00:21:57,481
- You know Ernie well?
- All my life.

104
00:21:57,649 --> 00:22:01,050
- He's always lived here?
- Yeah. Why?

105
00:22:07,125 --> 00:22:08,456
I should go.

106
00:22:59,978 --> 00:23:02,674
That's quite enough of you,
Sticky Feet.

107
00:24:13,218 --> 00:24:16,016
Ernie, have we met before?

108
00:24:16,188 --> 00:24:17,553
I don't think so.

109
00:24:21,293 --> 00:24:24,558
They say the same face can turn up
on different people. Isn't that so?

110
00:24:26,131 --> 00:24:27,496
Yeah, I guess so.

111
00:24:28,967 --> 00:24:30,867
Enjoy your book.

112
00:24:35,273 --> 00:24:36,501
Get back!

113
00:24:36,942 --> 00:24:39,172
You forget something, Claire?

114
00:24:40,512 --> 00:24:42,241
Did you forget something, miss?

115
00:24:44,483 --> 00:24:45,848
No.

116
00:27:03,755 --> 00:27:05,416
Hi.

117
00:27:11,096 --> 00:27:12,620
Morning.

118
00:27:15,300 --> 00:27:17,200
Good morning, Claire.

119
00:27:19,871 --> 00:27:21,600
Good morning.

120
00:27:22,707 --> 00:27:26,199
Was it the storm? You okay?

121
00:27:26,778 --> 00:27:28,473
Yeah, I'm fine.

122
00:27:34,719 --> 00:27:35,845
I bought your book.

123
00:27:37,055 --> 00:27:39,080
So you're the one.

124
00:27:40,291 --> 00:27:42,191
Fascinating history this place has.

125
00:27:45,296 --> 00:27:49,596
Listen, you wanna find out more,
I'll take any excuse to skip church.

126
00:27:49,768 --> 00:27:51,326
Please?

127
00:27:53,238 --> 00:27:57,231
So the Manville School for Boys
closed its doors in the late 1800s...

128
00:27:57,409 --> 00:27:59,673
...and the Westmoreland
Elementary School opened...

129
00:27:59,844 --> 00:28:02,574
...at the beginning
of the last century.

130
00:28:02,747 --> 00:28:05,375
How nice of the county
to invite the girls out to play.

131
00:28:05,550 --> 00:28:07,245
From what I know
of the boys' school...

132
00:28:07,419 --> 00:28:09,410
...the girls might have been
happier at home.

133
00:28:09,587 --> 00:28:12,954
- Scary.
- Good fodder for a new book.

134
00:28:14,359 --> 00:28:16,020
I just read The Swamp
to my niece...

135
00:28:16,194 --> 00:28:19,561
...and I gotta tell you,
I found it quite creepy.

136
00:28:19,731 --> 00:28:22,393
All the great children's books
are dark.

137
00:28:22,567 --> 00:28:26,333
Brothers Grimm, Aesop,
Roald Dahl.

138
00:28:26,504 --> 00:28:29,302
"Ring Around the Rosy"
was about dying from the plague.

139
00:28:29,474 --> 00:28:34,537
Scary monsters in
the deep dark marsh. Oh, scary.

140
00:28:35,080 --> 00:28:36,809
Fairy tales and nursery rhymes...

141
00:28:36,981 --> 00:28:40,144
...tap into the primal, subconscious
fears of the young mind.

142
00:28:40,318 --> 00:28:43,185
So you're saying that all kids
like to be creeped out.

143
00:28:43,354 --> 00:28:45,117
Didn't you?

144
00:28:45,790 --> 00:28:48,486
You ever hear any stories
about this place?

145
00:28:48,660 --> 00:28:50,685
Like what, like creepy ones?

146
00:28:51,196 --> 00:28:55,997
Creaking boards, slamming doors,
whistling winds...

147
00:28:56,534 --> 00:28:58,468
You writers.

148
00:28:58,970 --> 00:29:00,198
I'll tell you what.

149
00:29:00,371 --> 00:29:03,363
I'll tell you everything that I know
over dinner tomorrow.

150
00:31:52,744 --> 00:31:55,008
Platz! Platz! Platz!

151
00:31:55,280 --> 00:31:57,680
Platz. Platz.

152
00:31:58,616 --> 00:32:01,551
- Normally, he's a pussycat.
- Could have fooled me.

153
00:32:03,054 --> 00:32:05,579
- Are you Geoffrey Hunt?
- Hunt.

154
00:32:05,757 --> 00:32:08,351
- Everybody calls me Hunt.
- Claire Holloway.

155
00:32:08,526 --> 00:32:11,984
He hasn't blown his top like that
in a long time, Claire.

156
00:32:12,163 --> 00:32:14,393
Only one reason he does that.

157
00:32:14,565 --> 00:32:17,033
Oh, yeah? What's that?

158
00:32:20,805 --> 00:32:23,740
- He smells a ghost.
- What?

159
00:32:24,208 --> 00:32:28,872
Think of it like vapors
from the other side.

160
00:32:29,681 --> 00:32:31,308
I don't believe in ghosts.

161
00:32:33,318 --> 00:32:34,979
Neither do I.

162
00:32:35,820 --> 00:32:37,651
I'll follow you.

163
00:32:41,426 --> 00:32:42,688
So this place, huh?

164
00:32:42,860 --> 00:32:44,725
- You've been here before?
- Three years ago.

165
00:32:44,896 --> 00:32:46,124
What was her name? Grace?

166
00:32:46,297 --> 00:32:47,525
- Mercy.
- Yeah.

167
00:32:47,699 --> 00:32:51,931
So you're a paranormal consultant
who doesn't believe in ghosts?

168
00:32:52,103 --> 00:32:53,832
I believe in people.

169
00:32:54,005 --> 00:32:56,166
I mean,
people are water and energy.

170
00:32:56,341 --> 00:32:59,139
If water can transform from ice
into steam, into mist...

171
00:32:59,310 --> 00:33:03,644
...and energy transforms them,
why can't people?

172
00:33:04,382 --> 00:33:05,713
What happened with Mercy?

173
00:33:05,883 --> 00:33:09,649
She got a little spooked, that's all.
Noises and such. Nothing major.

174
00:33:09,821 --> 00:33:11,914
These kinds of energies
can be very particular.

175
00:33:12,090 --> 00:33:14,923
They can reveal themselves
to one person and not to another one.

176
00:33:15,093 --> 00:33:16,754
Why me?

177
00:33:17,762 --> 00:33:19,787
You tell me, Claire.

178
00:33:23,768 --> 00:33:25,759
He was in there?

179
00:33:32,877 --> 00:33:34,970
Port.

180
00:33:37,281 --> 00:33:38,942
Port?

181
00:33:41,686 --> 00:33:43,517
It's the access point for them
to come in.

182
00:33:43,688 --> 00:33:46,782
The computer's another good one.
I'd leave that off for now.

183
00:33:54,966 --> 00:33:56,934
How long has this been here?

184
00:33:58,403 --> 00:34:00,234
A couple of days. Why?

185
00:34:01,072 --> 00:34:03,097
On the other side...

186
00:34:04,642 --> 00:34:11,275
...doors can be both symbolic
and literal at the same time.

187
00:34:12,483 --> 00:34:14,246
Taking one down...

188
00:34:16,320 --> 00:34:18,982
...can be a way of stopping someone
from coming across.

189
00:34:20,258 --> 00:34:24,126
So when you put the door
back up...

190
00:34:25,496 --> 00:34:26,963
You're inviting them back in.

191
00:34:39,877 --> 00:34:42,710
There's a definite increase in energy.
That's for sure.

192
00:34:42,880 --> 00:34:45,440
- But why?
- People are weird.

193
00:34:45,616 --> 00:34:48,744
They die, they get weirder.

194
00:34:49,120 --> 00:34:51,418
Question is, why do you care?

195
00:34:52,824 --> 00:34:54,451
Because I've seen...

196
00:34:54,625 --> 00:34:57,594
I've seen that little girl before,
and not just in this house.

197
00:34:57,762 --> 00:35:00,060
Do you have any idea
what you're dealing with?

198
00:35:00,231 --> 00:35:03,723
It's a different world.
They don't play by your rules.

199
00:35:04,102 --> 00:35:08,334
I lost my wife and my little girl
seven years ago.

200
00:35:08,539 --> 00:35:12,532
I went looking for answers.
I never found them.

201
00:35:13,277 --> 00:35:15,040
So you need to think about that...

202
00:35:15,213 --> 00:35:17,647
...before you go looking for answers
on the other side.

203
00:35:17,815 --> 00:35:21,842
You wanna be amongst the living,
trust me.

204
00:35:26,057 --> 00:35:27,820
There's a motel in town.

205
00:35:28,659 --> 00:35:31,560
If I were you, I'd check in to it.

206
00:35:31,863 --> 00:35:33,728
Why make this your battle?

207
00:36:32,890 --> 00:36:38,260
My father used to say, "Hunt"...
He called me Hunt.

208
00:36:38,462 --> 00:36:41,829
He could be rather impersonal,
my father.

209
00:36:41,999 --> 00:36:48,495
He'd say, "Hunt, you can dodge the
draft, you can cheat on your taxes...

210
00:36:48,673 --> 00:36:51,801
...but never desert
a damsel in distress."

211
00:36:53,311 --> 00:36:55,677
Let's get this party started.

212
00:37:15,099 --> 00:37:17,499
What do they want from me?

213
00:37:18,669 --> 00:37:20,500
Don't know.

214
00:37:21,038 --> 00:37:22,801
But one thing's for sure.

215
00:37:23,574 --> 00:37:25,007
It's you that they want it from.

216
00:37:27,945 --> 00:37:29,640
Can you imagine?

217
00:37:29,947 --> 00:37:32,211
Can you imagine,
if Mercy had seen what you seen...

218
00:37:32,383 --> 00:37:36,012
...she'd be living in another country
under an assumed name.

219
00:37:37,188 --> 00:37:40,351
Can you stand there for a second?
Just for a second, please. Thank you.

220
00:37:43,661 --> 00:37:45,788
You are very photogenic.

221
00:37:54,038 --> 00:37:55,665
I hope you can see them too.

222
00:37:55,973 --> 00:37:58,134
Unless they're camera-shy...

223
00:37:58,643 --> 00:38:00,270
...we'll get them.

224
00:38:02,947 --> 00:38:04,915
So where did you grow up?

225
00:38:07,151 --> 00:38:08,948
All over.

226
00:38:13,224 --> 00:38:16,853
Oh, you're a military brat, huh?

227
00:38:17,194 --> 00:38:19,526
- No.
- Little sip.

228
00:38:21,599 --> 00:38:23,658
No, my parents were teachers.

229
00:38:26,170 --> 00:38:27,694
Where they from originally?

230
00:38:31,375 --> 00:38:34,173
Well, they weren't my birth parents.

231
00:38:35,379 --> 00:38:40,339
Well, how old were you
when you were adopted?

232
00:38:43,654 --> 00:38:46,487
- Eight.
- Eight?

233
00:38:48,826 --> 00:38:51,852
I bet you were a pretty little girl,
weren't you?

234
00:38:52,530 --> 00:38:55,897
Don't lie.
You were a cute one, weren't you?

235
00:38:57,301 --> 00:38:59,394
Unless you just sprouted up
all of a sudden...

236
00:38:59,570 --> 00:39:01,595
...and became just
what you are right now.

237
00:39:06,277 --> 00:39:09,713
My parents were killed
in a car accident.

238
00:39:12,283 --> 00:39:13,910
I see.

239
00:39:17,154 --> 00:39:19,019
You expecting someone?

240
00:39:23,294 --> 00:39:25,387
- Hey.
- Noah, I'm sorry.

241
00:39:25,563 --> 00:39:29,329
- I should have called you.
- Why? What happened?

242
00:39:31,435 --> 00:39:33,835
Hunt, Noah.

243
00:39:34,004 --> 00:39:35,494
Hunt's been helping me.

244
00:39:35,673 --> 00:39:37,937
- How's it going, Pitney?
- Hello.

245
00:39:41,979 --> 00:39:42,968
Let me guess.

246
00:39:43,147 --> 00:39:47,777
This has to do with those
creepy things you were talking about.

247
